Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the Windies' first innings! Joe Root and his men are out on the field. The Windies openers, Kraigg Brathwaite and John Campbell make their way out to the middle as well. Chris Woakes has the new red cherry in hand and is raring to go from the Malcolm Marshall end. Let's go...
... Second innings ...

West Indies will be a relieved team at the moment. They could have been staring down a total of way more than 507 but wickets in the middle session helped put a brake on the English onslaught. Kemar Roach was the outstanding bowler and picked up important wickets in the afternoon session as well in the post-Tea session. The pitch is still flat but the ball has started to turn with Veerasammy Permaul getting good purchase in the final session as he finished with 3 wickets. West Indies openers will have to lay down the marker and get themselves set so as to be able to counter the spin of Jack Leach later on. Early wickets will make things really tough for the hosts. The second innings of the Test match coming up in a bit.

Well, finally Joe Root has decided that they have enough runs on the board and England have declared with 507 runs on the board. After losing a wicket really early in the innings, the skipper Joe Root and Dan Lawrence put on a 164-run stand to give the English innings the impetus it needed on Day 1. On Day 2 it was all Ben Stokes as he hammered the Windies bowlers all around the park. The captain and vice-captain both made big centuries and Ben Foakes alongside Chris Woakes added additional runs to the total. England will now look to come out all guns blazing with the ball and all eyes will be on debutant Matthew Fisher and on how he bowls.

OUT! STUMPING! Joe Root calls their batters and that will be the end of England's innings. Tossed up, full and outside off, turn again. Leach comes down the track and looks to heave but misses and the ball sneaks through. Joshua Da Silva behind removes the bails easily. England declare their innings at 507/9.
Commentary.Howout: st Joshua Da Silva b Veerasammy Permaul

Commentary.Commentary: Tossed up, on off. Defended out.
FOUR! Tossed up, outside off. Leack steps down and smashes it through covers for a boundary.
Around off, fuller and this is blocked out.
Flatter and spinning around middle. Leach looks to defend but misses and gets hit high on the pads.
Another spicy short ball, over middle again. Fisher does well to get his head under it in time.
Short again, over middle. Matthew Fisher ducks under it.
Angled into the pads, Fisher misses the tuck and the ball goes off the pads towards the keeper.
Jack Leach is the new man in.

OUT! TAKEN! The short ball ploy has worked for Kemar Roach and the Windies and the last recognized batter is back in the hut. Roach steams in and digs in another short ball, around the batter's helmet. Chris Woakes looks to take it on as he makes a bit of room and attempts the swat. The ball goes off the toe end of the bat and towards mid-wicket. A couple of fielders converge but its Jayden Seales who runs in from deep mid-wicket and takes a fine sliding catch.
Commentary.Howout: c Jayden Seales b Kemar Roach

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Hoicked away and the 500 is up for England! Slower one, on the pads. Woakes gets down on one knee and whips it to the left of fine leg for a boundary.
Roach is pepping Woakes with good short balls. This is over leg stump and Woakes is just not ready for it. Luckily for him, there's no edge on that one.
On middle again, nudged onto the leg side.
Darted into middle. Blocked out.
The debutant, Matthew Fisher is out now.

OUT! STUMPED! Classic off-spinner's dismissal and Veerasammy Permaul has his man. Nicely flighted, outside off and on a driving length. Ben Foakes is enticed into playing the drive but the ball is slower and there's turn on offer too. Foakes gets beaten in flight and Joshua Da Silva has way too much time to whips off the bails. Foakes departs with a score of 499 and finally there's some respite for Permaul.
Commentary.Howout: st Joshua Da Silva b Veerasammy Permaul

Commentary.Commentary: On off, Chris Woakes uses his feet to drive it down towards wide long on for a single.
Around off, cut away off the back foot to deep point for one.
Nicely bowled! Drifted into middle, Foakes defends it out.
On middle, flicked away to mid-wicket.

Sliding into middle and leg, clipped away to deep square leg for a single. There hasn't been a single maiden over since the 73rd over of the innings and England inching ever closer to the 500-run mark.
Length this time, close to the off pole. Foakes defends it out.
Short ball, around off. This is pulled away through mid-wicket by Woakes for another single.
Quick single and they get through easily in the end. On middle, pushed towards mid on for a single.
Great stop from John Campbell. A length ball, on off. Foakes flicks it to the right of mid-wicket but can't get it past the fielder.
On the pads, nudged away onto the leg side for a quick single.
Quicker and flatter, around off. This is cut away through point for one.

FOUR BYES! Well, that's unlucky for the bowler. Nicely flighted and drifted into middle. Chris Woakes looks to step out but gets beaten in flight completely. The ball goes through bat and pad, eludes the keeper and races away into the fence.
Shorter and around off. Woakes goes on the back foot and punches it towards covers.
On a length, around off and there's a bit of turn as well. Ben Foakes works it to sweeper cover for a single.
Flatter and around off. Firmly pushed towards covers.
Appeal from the bowler but the keeper doesn't seem interested. Banged in short and down the leg side. Woakes looks to pull but misses.
A slower bumper now, outside off and the ball dies on its way to Joshua Da Silva.

FOUR! First boundary of the session and it comes off Woakes' bat. On a driving length, a bit wide of off stump. Woakes goes chasing after it and gets an outside edge that runs away into the third man fence.
A length ball, around off. This is dabbed down towards backward point.
Good short ball from Kemar Roach, a bit of an intent shown. On middle, at helmet height and Woakes just about manages to duck under it.
Runs straightaway. Pitched up on off, Foakes pushes it out towards covers for a single.
We are all set for the final session. Ben Foakes and Chris Woakes to resume their batting. Kemar Roach to start the last session.
... Day 2, Session 3...

Right then, the visitors seem to show no signs of slowing down and look to be well on course of scoring way over 500 runs. The question is when does Joe Root decide to declare. An interesting final session coming up at 12.30 am IST (7 pm GMT, previous day). Do join us then.

The man of the hour, Kemar Roach is up for a quick chat. He says it feels good to surpass Sir Garfield Sobers in the wickets tally but says there is still more work to do. Adds that the plan was to bowl straight, change angles and the luck was there. Tells that the pitch is dry and it does not spin much but he expects to spin more later in the next three days.

West Indies bowlers were better in the second session but still not quite upto the mark, not necessarily due to a lack of skill but more so due to the nature of the pitch. Kemar Roach got the big wicket of the English captain early in the session and in doing so surpassed the great Sir Garfield Sobers to grab the number 7th spot on the Windies all-time wicket-takers in Test matches. Alzarri Joseph too looked better and was rewarded with a wicket. The skipper, Kraigg Brathwaite used the lack of pace to put a seed of doubt in the batters' minds and even got Stokes out which was very much needed. But they couldn't press the issue forward and Veerasammy Permaul has remained largely ineffective. They will now want to clean up the visitors as soon as possible to get out there and have a prolonged batting session rather than a nervy one late in the evening.

Another session of Test cricket has flown by and to be honest, it has yet again belonged to the visitors. Even when they lost 3 wickets, they scored 113 runs in 29 overs and seem to be firmly in the driving seat. The skipper Joe Root was dismissed early in the session after surpassing 150 and then it was Ben Stokes who went on to score his 11th career ton in Test cricket. He got out looking to up the ante and Jonny Bairstow couldn't do much this time around. Foakes and Woakes though put on a steady stand of 58 runs to see England through to Tea on Day 2. They will now look to come out and get as many runs as possible and then put some pressure on the hosts with the ball late in the day.
Floated again, angling on off. Woakes looks to flick but gets an inside edge onto the pads. The ball lobs well wide of first slip. That will be Tea on Day 2.
An appeal for caught behind but not given! Floated, full and outside off. Woakes prods to defend but the ball turns shade away and gets beaten on the outside edge. The replay confirms no bat there.
Full and on off, pushed to long off for a single.
Another single as this is worked to deep cover.
Short and on off. Foakes makes room and losses his stance but still hits it to deep cover for a single.
Full, outside off, width given and this is driven to deep point for a single.
Full and on leg, swept to deep square leg for a single.
Full and on off. Foakes comes down and drills it to long off for one more.
Quicker this time, on middle. Woakes turns it to long on for a single. Kraigg Brathwaite steps over and a no ball is given.
On middle. Defended out.
FOUR! This was short and outside off, Woakes looks to cut but it goes of the outside edge to the third man fence. A 50-run stand between these two comes up...
Slow again, short and on off. Woakes cuts it to mid-wicket where the fielder makes a good stop.
Flatter and on off, very slow in the air. Blocked out.
Full and on off. Woakes drills it to long on for a single.
Floated, on off, pushed back to Permaul.
Tossed up,full and on off, it lands and spins away. Woakes looks to sweep it but misses and gets hit on the pads. A half-hearted appeal for LBW follows.
Full and on middle, pushed back to the bowler.
SIX! HUGE! Tossed up, full and outside off. Woakes slog-sweeps it over mid-wicket for a biggie.
Tossed up, on off. Defended out.
Shorter and angling across. Foakes defends with soft hands to first slip.
Down the leg side, Woakes sweeps it to fine leg for a single.
Flatter, quicker and on off. Woakes pushes back to the bowler.
Another solid block from Woakes.
Floated, full and on middle. Woakes on his front foot to block it.
Full and on the pads, flicked to deep square leg for a single.
Flatter and on off. Woakes defends it to covers.
On off. Blocked out.
Full and on off, pushed to long off for a single.
This one lands on off and spins away. Foakes lunges and defends it out.
Tossed up, on middle. Foakes prods and blocks it.
Angles a full ball, on off. Blocked out.
Looks like the ball has lost its shape and here comes the box full of balls. The umpire chooses one and we are ready to resume.
Outside off, driven towards covers for a single.
Around middle and leg, Foakes uses his feet again but this time there's a silly mid on in place.
This is spilled down the leg side, Woakes sweeps it down to fine leg for a run.
At just 69 kph, Ben Foakes comes down the track and drives it down to long on for a single.
Around off, pushed towards mid off.
Shorter in length, angled across off. Woakes rocks back and pushes it to long off for a single.
Around off, pushed towards covers.

Flatter this time and on off. Foakes reaches out to defend. It's all a bit slow out there at the moment. Something has to give and soon or else the visitors will keep on piling the runs, slowly but surely.
And again! Tossed up, on middle. Woakes pushes it through mid on for a single.
Drifted into middle and leg, worked to wide long on for one more.
On middle, flicked to mid-wicket.
Flatter, on off. Kept out on the off side.
This one almost never artives. At just 61 kph and on leg. Ben Foakes reaches out and brooms it to deep backward square leg for a run.
A bit of a fumble from Kraigg Brathwaite but he recovers well. On middle, firmly pushed towards the bowler who gets a hand on it but is quick to chase it down and stop the single.
On leg stump, flicked away towards short fine leg for an easy single.
Brathwaite darts this one in at 95 ckph. Woakes makes the block.
Considerably slowed up this time. Woakes blocks it out.
Pushed through on middle. Foakes clips it through mid-wicket for a single.
On the pads, nudged away on the leg side.
Looped up on middle. Foakes pushes it through mid off and collects a single.
Around off, pushed towards covers.
Slower through the air, flighted on middle. Woakes with a gentle push down the ground for a run. The 450 is up now for England.
On middle, driven through mid on for a single.
Lovely! Flighted, drift in towards off stump. The ball drips and turns after pitching. Foakes looks to blocks but gets beaten past the outside edge.
Brathwaite keeps it around leg and this is turned through square leg for a fifth single in the over.
Flighted delivery, around leg stump. Woakes knocks it 'round the corner and turns the strike over.
Drifted onto the pads, Ben Foakes tickles it behind square on the leg side for another single.
Slowed up, on middle. Foakes reaches out and pushes back to the bowler.
On the pads, worked to deep square leg by Woakes for one more.
This is floated outside off. Foakes walks towards the ball and pushes it to the left of mid off for a single.
Very full this time and Woakes jams it back to the bowler.
A loopy ball, on off, Foakes works it to covers for a single.
A single as this is pushed to long on.
A low dipping full toss, on middle, drilled to long on for one.
An arm ball, angling around off. Foakes defends on time.
Full and on off, pushed to covers.
Spin from both ends now as Veerasammy Permaul (27-1-97-1) is back into the attack.
An arm ball, on middle. Woakes strides forward and blocks it.
Darted on the pads. Ben tickles it to fine leg for a single.
Floated, on the pads, flicked to mid-wicket.
Flighted ball, on off, pushed to mid off.
Full and on middle. Foakes eases it to long on for a couple of runs.
Darted on the pads, Woakes turns it to mid-wicket for one more.
Length ball, outside off. Woakes on his toes taps it to covers for one more.
Another single as this length ball is pushed to long on.
On middle, Woakes hits it to mid-wicket for a single.
Almost chopped on! Short of a length, outside off. Woakes looks to pull but gets an inside edge, past the off stump and to fine leg. A single taken.
Length and outside off. Foakes punches it to deep point for a single.
Length ball, nipping back in around off. Foakes steps across and blocks it.
Floated, full and on middle. Woakes tucks it to mid-wicket.
A single as this full ball is flicked to deep square leg.
Slower ball, flighted and on middle, Foakes skips down and wrists it to mid-wicket.
Full and on middle, worked to mid-wicket.
Tossed up, full and on off. Foakes leans and blocks it to covers.
Full and angling on the pads. Woakes gets low and sweeps it to square leg for a single.
Length and outside off. Foakes lets it through.
FOUR! Foakes is off the mark with a boundary. Length ball, outside off. Foakes steers it through point for a boundary.
Length ball, outside off. Foakes offers no shot.
Length again, Foakes punches off the back foot to point.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone.
Fuller and outside off, pushed to covers.
On the pads, Woakes keeps it out. 14 runs and a big wicket of Stokes from the over.
Flighted, flatter and around off. Woakes on the back foot, works it to short mid-wicket.
Chris Woakes walks out to bat now.

OUT! TAKEN! Kraigg Brathwaite gets the big wicket. Ben Stokes tries to go big again but holes one out. A short ball again was way outside off. Stokes stands tall and tries to hit it over covers but it goes off the toe end of his bat, to deep cover where Shamarh Brooks takes it with ease. Ben Stokes gets a standing ovation for his wonderful knock.
Commentary.Howout: c Shamarh Brooks b Kraigg Brathwaite

Commentary.Commentary: SIX! Just, just over John Campbell! Shorter this time, on off. Stokes pulls it to wide of long on. John Campbell there tracks back and takes the catch but he stepped over the ropes and it goes for a maximum.
SIX! BANG! Slower through the air, flatter and around off. Stokes swings across and this goes right from the middle and over mid-wicket for a biggie.
Fuller and outside off. Stokes smacks it wide of deep cover for a couple of runs.
Skipper Kraigg Brathwaite brings himself back into the attack.
Length ball, closer this time but wide enough for Foakes to leave it alone.
Well outside off and Foakes is happy to leave it.
Length ball, angling on middle. Blocked out.

Drinks! After that onslaught in the opening session, the hosts have pulled up their socks a bit. Joe Root was sent back after a mammoth ton by Kemar Roach who bowled really well early in this session. Ben Stokes and Jonny Bairstow though looked positive too and Stokes went on to score his 11th Test ton. But Alzarri Joseph has got Bairstow out and the Windies will now look to get into the tail as soon as possible. Also, Ben Foakes walks out to bat at number 7.

OUT! TAKEN! Jonny Bairstow is livid with himself! Alzarri Joseph goes wide of the crease and angles a length ball, outside off. Bairstow thinks to hook it away but it goes off the leading edge, in the air and to deep mid-wicket where Nkrumah Bonner takes it. West Indies get the centurion in Antigua for a timid score this time.
Commentary.Howout: c Nkrumah Bonner b Alzarri Joseph

Commentary.Commentary: Around off, pushed to covers for a single.
Short in length, around off, extra bounce there. Stokes looks to ramp it away but gets beaten by the bounce.
West Indies have gone full defensive as mostly all the players are standing in the deep. This is full and on middle. Stokes hits it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Might be the back of the hand delivery, around off, pulled to deep square leg for a single.
A length ball, around off. Bairstow defends it to point.
Length ball, way outside off. Stokes slaps it to long off for a single.
Another single as this is pushed to point.
Very full and outside off. Stokes works it to long off for a single.
Overpitched, on middle, flicked to deep mid-wicket for an easy couple.
Short ball, drifting on middle. Bairstow keeps his bat close to his body and watches it bounce over.
Fuller ball, on middle. Bairstow pushes it softly to mid on.
On the pads this time, Stokes bunts it to deep square leg for a single.
Length again, slanting on middle, tucked to mid-wicket.
Length and down the leg side. Stokes misses his flick.
A length ball, on off. Bairstow keeps it out.
On middle, Bairstow defends it off the front foot.
FOUR! Easy pickings for Jonny Bairstow. Short and wide, it's the back of the hand slower ball. Bairstow picks it up and slaps it through cover-point for a boundary. England go past the 400-run mark.
Pitched up, angling into off. Bairstow presses forward to defend.
On middle, pushed down to long on for a single.
Back of a length, around off. Stokes hangs back and taps it towards covers.
On off again, Bairstow stays solid in defense.
Good-length, on off. Tapped towards covers.

A century to savour for Ben Stokes! The crowd is up on its feet and Stokes looks up to the heavens and up to his late father. Length, around off, bunted out on the off side. Jonny Bairstow is alive to the situation and responds quickly. They scamper through and Stokes has his first hundred in the Caribbean.
Use of the feet from Ben Stokes and maybe some jitters out there as he's on 99. A length ball, slanting in from off and Stokes taps it towards covers.
On off, defended off the front foot towards cover.
Pitched up from 'round the wicket and around the fifth stump line, Stokes shoulders arms to it.
Pitched up on middle and leg. Bairstow defends it towards short mid-wicket yet again.
Full and straight, punched towards mid on.
This time, on the pads. Defended to short mid-wicket.
Fuller, around off and nipping in. Bairstow manages to keep it out.
Nicely bowled! Slanted into middle and leg. Bairstow looks to turn it leg side but gets a leading edge towards covers.
Back of a length, close to the off pole. Stokes hops and nudges it down to deep backward point for one.
On a good length, around off. Bairstow hangs back and keeps it out on the off side.
This is spilled down the leg side, Bairstow misses the flick.
On off, pushed away towards cover.
FOUR! Back-to-back boundaries for Jonny Bairstow. Half-volley, on off. Bairstow keeps his head still and exquisitely pushes it through covers for another boundary.
FOUR! Straight as an arrow! Overpitched on off, Jonny Bairstow with a lovely straight drive back past the bowler and the ball races away to the fence.
Full and on off, driven straight to mid off.
Sliding down the leg side, helped down to fine leg for a run by Bairstow.
Right on the money from Roach. Jonny Bairstow stays solid in defense.
Roach bowls it slower at just 103 clicks and on middle. Ben Stokes uses his wrists to turn it down to long on for a run.
Pitched up, around off. Stokes punches it firmly back towards the bowler.
Misfield and they steal a single. Fuller and on the pads. Bairstow clips it straight to Jermaine Blackwood at mid-wicket who lets it through and allows the single.
Around middle and slanting into the pads. Bairstow flicks it awkwardly towards mid-wicket.
Full and outside off, driven to the left of mid off for a quick single.
Fuller and on off. This is hit to mid-wicket.
Short of a length, slower and outside off. Stokes dabs it softly to deep point for a single.
Very full and on middle. Stokes makes room and smashes it on the up but just short of mid off.
Fullish and outside off. Stokes is right behind the line to keep it out.
Full and outside off. Stokes gently defends it on the off side.
Two leg byes! Fuller and angling on the pads. Bairstow misses his flick. It goes off the pads to fine leg for two leg byes. Good running.
Fuller and on off. Stokes plays it to long on for a single.
Length and outside off. Stokes offers no shot.
Fuller and on middle. Stokes flicks it to deep mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
A fuller ball, outside off. Stokes blocks it very late, off the bottom part of the blade.
Roach goes wide of off stump and Stokes shoulders arms.
Full and outside off. Left alone by Bairstow.
Length this time, angled into off. Bairstow defends it out.
On off, pushed back to the bowler.
On a nagging length and in that channel outside off. This is left alone.
Full and on off, driven towards wide mid off for a quick single.
Pitched up, close to the off stump, from 'round the wicket. Stokes lets it through to the keeper.
Width on offer and Stokes taps it past point for a single. He will retain strike as well.
Full and outside off, left alone.
This is angled into middle, Jonny Bairstow is off the mark with a flick through mid-wicket.
A length ball, around off. Bairstow plays it towards point.
Attacking the stumps and Bairstow defends it out.
Jonny Bairstow is the new batter in.

OUT! LBW! Brilliant call from Jason Holder at first slip to press the issue and go for the review. This is a fullish delivery, around off and nipping back in quite a fair bit. Joe Root falls over a bit as he looks to push it out. The ball goes through the defense and raps him on the pads. The visitors appeal but they seem it's angling down leg. Holder pushes for the review and Brathwaite goes for it. No spike on UltraEdge and Ball Tracker comes up with three reds. Joe Root has to walk to huge applause after a wonderful knock and Kemar Roach moves up to 7th place in the leading wicket-takers for the Windies in Test cricket, surpassing Sir Garfield Sobers.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Kemar Roach

Commentary.Commentary: Review. West Indies take the LBW decision upstairs. UltraEdge shows no bat. Ball Tracking shows three reds and finally, West Indies get the better of Root.
Roach to start the session from the other end.
Open spaces on either side of the pitch and that's an easy single for Joe Root. Back of a length, on off. Root hops back and nudges it towards cover-point for a run.
On off, eased down to long on for one more.
Holder bowls the cutter now, slow and on off. Joe Root works it towards square leg and turns the strike over. One-day tactics coming into play now and the field is well spread.
Pitched up, well outside off. Root watches it all the way through and makes the leave.
A length ball, slanting down the leg side. Root shuffles across and looks to flick it away but misses.
Holder starts off with a floater, on middle. Ben Stokes punches it down to long on for a single. Moves into the 90s now.
We are back for the post-Lunch session. Joe Root and Ben Stokes to continue their innings. Jason Holder to proceed the innings.
... Day 2, Session 2...

Apart from the first 30 minutes, West Indies looked tired in their effort. After a tight start, the bowlers bowled too many outside off deliveries and they were punished for that. Permaul precisely was taken to cleaners by Stokes and went for boundaries in each over. The pitch is flat but the inconsistency is making it worse for the hosts and didn't bowl a single maiden over in the first session. If they fail to bowl better lengths, expect the same outing for the Windies, which they would not like at all. The second session will start at 10.10 pm IST (4.40 pm GMT) Do join us then.

Another excellent session for England, 125 runs scored without any wickets lost, solid! While Root added just 32 runs to his overall tally, it was Stokes who took on the Windes bowlers as he scored runs at a quick rate. Root brought up his 150 while Stokes was going all counterattack from the other end. He is just 11 runs away from welcoming the triple-digit score. England will look for a score around 550-600 and with the way they are playing, they look in no mood to stop the carnage.
Brathwaite goes quicker, full and straight on the final ball. Joe Root digs it out and that will be Lunch on Day 2.
This is slowed up considerably again, just around 70 clicks. Root waits for it and works it towards square leg.
On middle, driven towards mid on.
Ouch! That is not advisable. Tossed up, on off. Stokes with a firm uppish drive, wide of the bowler and Kraigg Brathwaite just sticks out a left boot. The batters get a single.
Root premeditates with the reverse sweep and Brathwaite slows it up considerably. Root gets it down to third man and picks up a single.

Floated, very full and around leg stump. This is quicker at 91 clicks and Joe Root attempts the reverse sweep. He gets taken aback by the pace of the ball and the ball hits Root on the pads. A stifled appeal from the bowler.
Kraigg Brathwaite to bowl now.

Very full, on off. This is pushed down to long on for a single. Joe Root gets to his 150 and there is a huge roar from the crowd. Root raises his bat and it has been another classy innings from the English skipper.
Slower bouncer now on middle. Joe Root plays a lovely controlled pull shot and pulls it along the ground towards deep backward square leg for a couple.
Holder bowls another off cutter, around off. Root blocks it out on the off side.
Slower again, on off. Stokes presses forward and pushes it towards extra cover for a run.
Holder comes from 'round the wicket and hurls across a slower length ball on middle. Stokes defends it back onto the deck.
Fullish delivery, floated up around off. Root bunts it out to cover-point for a single.
Jason Holder to steam in and try and stop the counterattack.

SIX! My word! This is something special we are witnessing here. Right in the slot outside off. Ben Stokes hangs back and smokes it a long, long way over the long on fence. This also brings up 5000 runs for him in Test cricket, becoming the 23rd English batter to do so.
Stokes will feel he missed out on that one. Short and wide, Stokes hangs back and slaps it towards covers.

TWO LEG BYES! Two called straightaway and they race back for the second with ease in the end. On the pads, Stokes misses the flick and the ball goes off the pads behind square on the leg side. A couple of leg byes taken.

FOUR! Make that a hat-trick of boundaries now and Ben Stokes is eyeing a century before the Lunch break. This is pushed wider, Stokes moves outside off and drags it through mid-wicket for another boundary.
FOUR! This is started to become a nightmare for the hosts now. Pitched up, on off. Ben Stokes goes up and over extra cover and picks up back-to-back boundaries. 350 up for England.

FOUR! Poor bowling from Joseph. A length ball, width on offer and Stokes drives through the line and the ball races away to the cover fence. 100 partnership is up between these two and even more than 100 runs scored in the first session already.
This is pushed through on off. Root hangs back to defend.
Fuller and on off. Stokes reverse paddles it to deep backward point for a run.
FOUR! Floated up, around off. Stokes hits it firmly off the back foot and goes over covers. He picks up another boundary.

SIX! Muscled! Permaul holds the length back and bowls it on middle. Ben Stokes rocks back and pulls it all the way over the mid-wicket fence for a biggie. He was hitting against the wind there, but he doesn't care.
Well, that was flashy! Ben Stokes switches to a right-hander and Permaul bowls it quicker around leg stump. Stokes misses the hard sweep and there's a bit of an extra bounce as well.
A touch quicker, spilled well down the leg side. Left alone.
Excellent delivery! Good-length, close to the off pole. The ball straightens and zips past the outside edge of Root's blade as he has a half poke at it.

PITCH REPORT - Mark Butcher is pitchside. Butcher says its a bit cooler and there's a bit more cloud cover today. Mentions that there's a bit of roughness and that means the ball will start to grip a little bit and there might even be some reverse swing. Says as the Test match goes on, bowlers will enjoy bowling on this surface and there will be movement as well. He is then joined by Windies pacer Jayden Seales. Seales says that he feels refreshed now after a hard day yesterday. Adds that there's not much difference in the pitch from the one in the first Test and it got flatter and flatter as the day went on. Mentions that they need to get them out to a decent total and then bat well. Adds that they will look to attack the new batter and lay down the marker early.

Debutant Matthew Fisher is up for a chat. He says he was training a day before while he got to know that he was making his debut. Adds that it was special to get the debut cap from Root and feels he is the greatest ever. Tells that with the ball they need to be brave early on and then spinners should help them.

West Indies went in with an unchanged team which was understandable and Jayden Seales gave them the perfect start by dismissing Crawley for a duck. It eased out for the batters after that but Veerasammy Permaul did get a breakthrough in the second session and the trend of just picking up one wicket in the entire session continued as Jason Holder dismissed Lawrence in the 90th over and the hosts will be looking to put on a much better display with the ball early on Day 2 or they could be out there in the field for the entirety of the day's play. Will Joe Root continue on his merry way? Or will the Windies take advantage of the breakthrough from last evening? We'll find out. The first session coming up in a bit.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 2 of the second Test match between West Indies and England from Kensington Oval in Barbados. Nothing much happened on the first day and it was a fairly even contest between bat and ball but the visitors on the back of a brilliant 164-run stand with the skipper Joe Root and Dan Lawrence made sure they had the upperhand early in this match. Lawrence fell in the final over of the day on 91 but the skipper is still out in the middle having surpassed his century, with a fair bit of luck one must say but sometimes you need the rub of the green to go your way and will look to put his team in a commanding position on Day 2.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

The wicket is very flat at least it was on Day 1 and England will be eyeing a big first innings score. West Indies, on the other hand, need to be a little more disciplined on Day 2 and need to hang on to their chances. Another good day of cricket awaits and the action begins at 7:30 pm IST (2:00 pm GMT) But as usual, our build-up will begin in advance. So, do join us then! Till then, goodbye!

West Indies, on the other hand, were really good for the first session and a half. They got the two wickets and also made run-scoring tough for England. However, they had no answers to the counter attack by Root and Dan Lawrence. The fielding was also not at its best as both were given a chance at least. That wicket right at the end though will really lift their morale heading into Day 2 and with the second new ball relatively new, they will hope they can get a couple of more wickets quickly.

The start wasn't all that easy for England! It was testing times for them with the new ball as it was doing a bit but England weathered that storm by losing just the one wicket in the first session. Then there was a stand that steadied the ship between Joe Root and Alex Lees. The latter fell after getting off to a start but Root continued along with Lawrence. The two scored freely and that is when the tide started shifting towards England. The two added over 150 runs in decent time with Root scoring yet another ton. Lawrence seemed all set for his hundred but he gave it away right at the end of the day.

A wicket right at the stroke of Stumps will help West Indies sleep a little better but have to say, the day has belonged to England and the charge is led by their skipper, Joe Root who walks off to a standing ovation and he deserves every bit of it.

OUT! CAUGHT! Oh, dear! Disappointment for Dan Lawrence but Jason Holder is sure happy! He punches the air in delight. England will certainly be the happier side at the end of the second session! Although they have lost just one wicket in this session, they have started to score runs freely. Joe Root did get a life, as he was dropped by Joshua Da Silva, but he is cruising along nicely. Dan Lawrence too has looked comfortable at the crease. He came in with positive intent has been looking in good touch. The duo have put together 56 runs, and are scoring at a much better rate. With the pitch assisting the batters, they will be hoping to go come out and just keep scoring runs. It's been tough for West Indies though. They did drop the catch of Joe Root which is proving to be costly and will continue to hurt them. Veerasammy Permaul did grab the wicket of Alex Lees, but since then it's been only England! The pitch as well does not have much to offer, we can see there is very less movement now, and it is getting difficult for the bowlers to grab wickets. We have another entertaining session coming up. Do join us back at 12:30 am IST (6:30 pm, previous day) for the final session.

England on the other hand did not score freely but they will be happy with the fact that they have lost just the one wicket. The first session is probably the toughest to bat and they have weathered the storm. Now, they would want to cash in and both the batters who are well-set, Lees and Root will look to go big. An interesting session awaits. Do join us at 10:10 pm IST (4:40 pm GMT) for the second session to find out what happens.

End of a gripping session of Test cricket and have to say both sides will be happy heading into the break. West Indies, will be disappointed they only took one wicket after picking one early, they did have a chance to get Root but did not review. They though will be pleased that they have given nothing away and if they manage to get a few quick wickets after the break, they will surely be on top. Most of their bowlers bowled with great control. However, they could be a little more straighter than they were in this session.

We are ready for live action! The players are out in the middle. First, they will take the knee in support of the BLM movement. Alex Lees and Zak Crawley will open the batting for England. Kemar Roach will begin with the ball. Here we go...

PITCH REPORT - Samuel Badree tells us about the conditions and the pitch. He says that there are clear blue skies and the sun is beaming down. The on-field is quick here in Barbados. The pitch looks on the dry side, there are some patches of grass, which could help the pacers get some variable bounce. He adds that it will be challenging on the first day, but it will get better as the match progresses.

Kraigg Brathwaite, the skipper of West Indies, says he was looking to bat first too but there might be some moisture and he hopes they can use it. States Nkrumah Bonner led by example in the last game and they put up a good fight. Informs they are playing the same team. Ends by saying there is always good spirit between West Indies and England and it’s always good.

Joe Root, the skipper of England, says that it looks like a good wicket, they would like to make first use of it, and he says that if there's any moisture it can move around a bit and he hopes he can start a bit stronger this time. Adds that they have two changes, Matthew Fisher and Saqib Mahmood are all set to make their debut and he is very excited for them.

West Indies (Unchanged Playing XI) - Kraigg Brathwaite (C), John Campbell, Shamarh Brooks, Nkrumah Bonner, Jermaine Blackwood, Jason Holder, Joshua Da Silva (WK), Alzarri Joseph, Kemar Roach, Veerasammy Permaul, Jayden Seales.

England (Playing XI) - Alex Lees, Zak Crawley, Joe Root (C), Dan Lawrence, Ben Stokes, Jonny Bairstow, Ben Foakes (WK), Chris Woakes, Matthew Fisher (On debut) (In for Craig Overton), Jack Leach, Saqib Mahmood (On debut) (In for Mark Wood).
TOSS - England have won the toss and they have elected to BAT first.

We have some news! England had announced their playing XI, but they had to make a change. Matthew Fisher will also make his Test debut since Craig Overton fell unwell overnight. So, three debutants in two matches, England are starting fresh here!

The hosts will be satisfied with the result of the first Test. Nkrumah Bonner and Jason Holder showed great resilience and determination in a tense final session on the fifth day. Although West Indies put up a great show, they will be a tad disappointed after losing two vital World Test Championship points due to a slow over rate. As expected, the hosts have named an unchanged 13-man squad for the second test. But, who will make it to the XI? We will find out soon. Stay tuned for the toss and team news.

England have a lot of positives to take from the first Test. They would be mighty pleased with seeing Zak Crawley getting a century and resolving England's top-order batting woes. Jack Leach and Ben Stokes too had not been at their best, but they showed great character and put up a fine performance as well. England will need them to replicate the same. The visitors have already announced that they have made a change in their lineup. Speedster, Saqib Mahmood is all set to make his Test debut, he will replace the injured Mark Wood in the squad.

We have witnessed a thrilling Test at Karachi between Australia and Pakistan just a few minutes ago, and we are in for yet another thrilling contest as West Indies take on England in the second Test at Barbados. The opening Test of this series ended in a stalemate, but let’s hope the pitch in Barbados has a lot more to offer, and we get to see some entertaining cricket. Both sides have some quality in their ranks and we can expect some electrifying action in the next 5 days. On that note, welcome to the coverage of the second Test.
... SECOND TEST ...

We are back! The players stride out to the middle after receiving a pep talk from Kraigg Brathwaite. Alex Lees and Zak Crawley are the openers for England. Kemar Roach to open the bowling for West Indies. Let's go...
... THIRD INNINGS ...

England now have around 15 overs to bat today and we probably will see them get their ODI mode out. Windies on the other hand, will probably look for a few wickets. It has been quite a dull day so far but we can well be in for some entertainment in the last hour or so.

Credit to the England bowlers, despite for being out there for so long, the energy levels just never went down. There was nothing on offer for them from the wicket but they still kept trying. Each of their bowlers had good economy rates to show for as they were very disciplined. Stokes though was the one who was causing a lot of problems. He was relentless with his lines and length. Leach did well too. Saqib and Fisher showed a lot of promise. Woakes will be happy with the lines and lengths he bowled and he got success as well. Jack Leach also became the first England bowler to bowl 69-plus overs in the first innings of a Test match since 1992 and fittingly ended the West Indies' innings. England in the end will be relieved and pleased they have managed to bowl out the hosts.

Finally, West Indies’ marathon innings comes to an end! They will be pleased with their effort as they have given themselves a chance of saving this Test now. This innings for them was about their skipper and their vice captain. Apart from the two, nobody really had a significant contribution. It was the 183 run stand between the two which bailed the Windies out of trouble. Both scored tons and led from the front for their side. Had there been more from the rest, Windies might have just taken the lead.

Nothing on UltraEdge. Ball Tracking shows all three reds. England bowlers can take a breather now. West Indies are all out for 411. England have a lead of 96 runs.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Jack Leach

Then there was some resistance shown by Joshua and Brathwaite. However the third new ball really worked well for the visitors as they got two wickets. Credit to the England bowlers who have bowled with a lot of energy despite the amount of time they have spent out there. Also, the wicket has also started to play tricks now. They would hope to take the remaining two quickly after the break. Windies on the other hand, will hope the lower order adds as many runs as possible. England on the other hand, continued to toil hard! The wicket seemed to have flatten even more as there was absolutely nothing in it for the bowlers. They though did manage to keep it tight but wickets is what they were looking for and they got just the one on the bowling of Stokes who probably was the pick of the bowlers in this session. They will need to continue to be patient and hope there is some sort of a collapse. At present we really do not see that happening. Stay tuned for another important session which will begin at 10.40 pm IST (5.10 pm GMT).

That is a solid session for the Windies! We said the first session could well dictate as to which was this game is going and for now, it seems like it is heading towards a draw. The hosts lost just the one wicket and have got the deficit down to just around 150. Both Joseph and Brathwaite showed great resistance early on and added above 50 before Joseph fell. Holder then has showed good solidness to hang in there with Brathwaite. More of the same is what they would want after the break.

FOUR! Flashed away! Back of a length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite throws his hands and cuts it to third man for a boundary.
On a length, on off. Kraigg Brathwaite taps it towards covers off the back foot.
Back of a length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite slashes it through cover-point for a brace.
Saqib Mahmood comes into the attack now. He replaces Matthew Fisher.
Fuller, around off. Joseph blocks it out.
Absolute ripper! Tossed up, outside off, spinning away. Alzarri Joseph prods and looks to defend. But the ball goes past the outside edge and just goes over the middle stump.
Flatter and quicker, on off. Alzarri Joseph keeps it out.
Floats it up, outside off. Alzarri Joseph fends it away to the off side.
On off, blocked out.
Loopy ball, on off. Alzarri Joseph punches it towards covers off the back foot.
FOUR! Cut away in the gap! Short of a length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite stays deep and cuts it hard behind point. That went off like a bullet. A boundary!
Short ball again, on middle and leg. Kraigg Brathwaite ducks underneath.
Back of a length, on off. Kraigg Brathwaite hops and offers a straight bat.
On a good length, around off, some extra bounce on that one. Kraigg Brathwaite is taken aback by that but manages to fend it on the leg side.
Goes full this time, on off. Kraigg Brathwaite drives it to mid off.
Short ball, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite sits under it.
Loopy ball, on middle. Joseph blocks it watchfully.
On off, blocked out.
Flatter, on the pads. Kraigg Brathwaite looks to defend. The ball goes off the inside edge and hits him on the pads. Lobs to backward square leg for a single. 300 up for West Indies!
Full and outside off, Kraigg Brathwaite prods and defends it off the outer half to backward point.
Flatter and quicker, at 88 kph, on off. Kraigg Brathwaite defends it out.
Tossed up, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite defends it well.
Good-length ball, around the fourth stump channel. Alzarri Joseph watches it closely and decides to leave it alone.
Short ball again, on middle. Alzarri Joseph ducks under it.
An effort ball from Matthew Fisher, on off. Alzarri Joseph sways away from the line and lets it go.
On a length, on off. Alzarri Joseph keeps it out.
FOUR! Lovely stroke! Length ball, outside off. Alzarri Joseph drives it behind point. Zak Crawley gives it a chase but the ball wins the race.
Back of a length, on off. Alzarri Joseph stands tall and meets it with a dead bat.
Floats it up, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite lunges forward. Defends it off the outer half to backward point. Just 2 runs off Leach's over!
Full and on middle, kept out by Kraigg Brathwaite.
Loopy ball, on off, turning away. Kraigg Brathwaite taps it to the off side.
Tossed up nicely, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite blocks it from the crease.
Fuller length, on middle and leg. Kraigg Brathwaite defends it on the leg side.
Loopy ball to start with, down leg. Kraigg Brathwaite hangs back and clips it to deep square leg. Calls for two and gets it easily.
Jack Leach to operate from the other end.
On a length, leg-lined. Alzarri Joseph tries to tuck but the ball brushes his pads and rolls to the keeper.
On a length, on middle. Joseph works it to short mid-wicket.
Short ball to Alzarri Joseph, on middle. Alzarri Joseph doesn't offer any shot and takes a blow on the gloves.
Fuller in length, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite flicks it to deep square leg for a single.
Length ball, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite nudges it to mid-wicket.

FOUR! Runs straightaway on Day 4! A loosener from Matthew Fisher, on the pads. Kraigg Brathwaite helps it on it's way to fine leg. Ben Foakes dives to his left but could not stop the ball from racing away.

We are ready for Day 4 action! Joe Root makes his way out in the middle leading his troops. Kraigg Brathwaite and Alzarri Joseph walk out to resume their innings. Matthew Fisher will begin the proceedings with the ball. Here we go...

PITCH REPORT - Mark Butcher is near the pitch. He says that there's an area which is crumbly and there's a good bare patch in the middle. Tells that there's plenty of rough but it is a long way outside off stump for the right-handers, but most of it is around the bowler's landing area. Mentions that if the batters are absolutely intent on staying in and not taking risks, it's gonna be hard work for the bowlers.

Dan Lawrence is down for a chat. He says if you offered him 90 odd at the start of the day, he would have taken it but he is disappointed he did not get to a ton. Adds he is happy to get his team into a good position. States if he did not hit those boundaries it might have been different, it is a good wicket to bat on and he should have left it alone (stroke that got him out) but Stokes got his ton next day and it turned out well. Reckons a couple of batters who might have not played him might be uncomfortable with his action, he tries to spin it hard and he might not always bowl good balls.

Jermaine Blackwood is up for a chat. Blackwood says when he got to the crease he was told by the skipper to get to a start, he knew if he got to a start he could go big. Adds the wicket is not easy to just come in and score and it was a crucial knock and he enjoyed batting with Brathwaite. States it is important to get past the follow-on and the first hour will be crucial and that is where they’ll need to be good.

Weather update - The news from the middle is that the rains have been on and off but right now, the good news is that it is not raining. The covers were on earlier but now they are coming off. The groundstaff are working on the pitch and if the rain does not arrive again, the play will begin at 7.45 pm IST (2.15 pm GMT). Stay tuned!

The visitors on the other hand, might feel if they do get Kraigg Brathwaite, it could well trigger into a collapse. They would love a lead of around 150 as they can surely push for a win after that. They would dearly hope the wicket deteriorates a lot more.

The hosts are still 20 runs a drift from avoiding the follow-on. That though should not be an issue with the amount of wickets left. They though need to keep doing the good work and one believes Brathwaite holds the key. He needs to continue his innings and hope the rest give him able support. They are doing well for now but it is a new day and things can change quickly.

A lot of will, determination, patience and grittyness was on display by the Windies skipper and vice captain. Courtesy the two, this Test also seems to be heading towards a draw, it will be the 4th draw if that happens in 6 Tests in recent times. However, the slow going by the hosts means England are still well and truly capable of sneaking in a win if they manage to get wickets quickly. The first session could be one which kind of indicates which way the game is heading into.

Right then! That concludes the play of Day 3. The penultimate day will start at 7.30 pm IST (2 pm GMT). But as usual, the build up will begin much earlier. So do join us for the same. Till then goodbye and take care.

Jermaine Blackwood is up for a quick chat. He says that he is happy with his performance today and after a slow start, it got easier for batting. Adds that he and Brathwaite just looked to stay out there for as long as possible and he is pleased with his effort. On being asked about his dismissal, he says that he completely misjudged that one as he thought the ball was bouncing much more than it did. About that fiery encounter with Stokes, he says that he likes playing against Stokes and has been doing so since the under-19 days and loves a bit of banter as well.

West Indies will be slightly disappointed as they lost Blackwood late in the evening and they know they are way behind in this match. The good news is they have their skipper, Kraigg Brathwaite out. Just like England, West Indies captain and vice-captain both scored centuries and would have loved the partnership to continue but the slight lapse of concentration saw the stand of 183 collapse. West Indies are still 219 runs behind in this match and it will take some effort from them to get a positive result out of this match with just two days remaining. The same goes for England as well who need a flurry of wickets at the start of Day 4 for any chance of winning from here.

England started the session on a high and they end on the front foot as well. A tiring day for the tourists but they will be happy to get the big wicket of Blackwood just near the end of the day. The lines and lengths were good from England today, Leach and Saqib Mahmood precisely as the latter got the wicket of Blackwood but that turned out to be a no ball while Foakes had a stumping chance off Leach but he too fumbled in his job and that helped Brathwaite survive. England would have loved the wicket of Brathwaite as well but the tiredness showed up as the day progressed.

NOT OUT! Drama on the final delivery of Day 3 but Alzarri Joseph survives. This is flighted again, on a length and on off. The ball turns in sharply. Joseph strides out to block but misses and gets rapped on the pads. The fielder at silly point pouches it and they all go up in unison. The review is taken and there is no spike on UltraEdge. The lbw is also checked but the ball is going miles down the leg side. Alzarri Joseph negotiates the final over and that will be curtains on Day 3.

Day 3, last ball and a review is taken. England take a review for a catch. UltraEdge shows no bat there. Not quite sure why the third umpire is taking so much time there as the evidence is there. Ball Tracking shows wickets missing and that will be it.
On off, blocked out.
FOUR! A half-volley around off and with all the fielders in and around the bat, Alzarri Joseph takes on the cover drive. He creams it to the cover fence and gets off the mark.
Around off, dabbed down past point but the batters do not take the run.
Shorter and on off. Kept out by Joseph.
Flighted, outside off and inviting the drive. Alzarri Joseph plays a loose shot as he looks to drive, gets beaten past the outside edge.
Floated on middle and leg, Brathwaite blocks it off with ease.
Flatter and on middle. Brathwaite hangs back to defend.
This is pushed through on middle and leg. Brathwaite dead-bats it.
On middle, defended under the eye line by Brathwaite.
This is skidded through on middle. Brathwaite is a little late in his front foot defense.
On off, pushed towards short mid off.
Close to the off pole and this one drifts in but doesn't spin much. Joseph looks to block but the ball slides past the outside edge. Yet another maiden over for England.
Nicely bowled! Flighted, a bit fuller and around off. The ball turns in and Joseph makes a watchful block.
On off, stroked away on the off side.
A tad shorter, on middle. Joseph rocks back and keeps it out.
On a driving length, outside off. Alzarri Joseph pushes it past silly point.
Turning in from around off, Joseph gets an inside edge past short leg.
Drifted into middle, defended off the front foot. Maiden!
On middle, kept out yet again.
Leach pulls back the length a bit and bowls it on off. Brathwaite goes on the back foot to defend.
This is drifted onto the pads. Blocked.
Flatter, around off. Brathwaite nudges it on the off side.
Drifted onto middle, Brathwaite strides out and blocks it out with soft hands.
Floated up, around off. This is kept out on the off side. A wicket-maiden for Dan Lawrence.
On off, Joseph strides out to defend. Much better from him.
Not holding back Alzarri Joseph but that's risky. Shorter on off, Joseph hangs back and looks to pull it away but mistimes it towards mid-wicket.
Nicely bowled! Looped up, full and around off. Joseph looks to drive it through covers but gets completely undone in flight.
Floated up, around off. Joseph caresses it towards point.
Alzarri Joseph will be the night-watchman for West Indies.
Review! Jermaine Blackwood takes a review after being given LBW. No shot was offered. Ball Tracking shows three reds and that is the end of Blackwood.

OUT! LBW! Well, what happened here? A moment of real lapse in concentration from Jermaine Blackwood and he has to walk back. This is nicely flighted, on a length and around off. The ball turns in and Blackwood shoulders arms. He gets trapped in plumb in front and the finger is raised. It is reviewed but Blackwood doesn't seem confident. No shot was offered so impact doesn't matter. Ball Tracker shows that it is hitting middle stump and Blackwood is livid with himself. Dan Lawrence has done it again as he gets the wicket of yet another centurion and its the end of a brilliant knock from Blackwood.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Dan Lawrence

Commentary.Commentary: Full and angling on the pads. Brathwaite tucks it to mid-wicket.
Another solid block from Brathwaite.
On middle, fuller and this one is blocked out.

Is that a chance? Yes, Ben Foakes has missed a stumping chance. Full and angling down the leg side. Brathwaite strides forward to defend but misses and the ball goes to the keeper. Brathwaite was well out but Foakes failed to grab it and the ball hits his pads. A chance goes begging for England.
Tossed up, on middle. Defended out.
Short and on middle. Jermaine whacks it to deep mid-wicket for a single.

Tossed up, on off, pushed back to Dan.

Full and on noff. Blackwood stretches forward to defend it.
Drift and spin for Dan Lawrence, Tossed up and on middle. Blackwood keeps it out.
A slider, angling on the pads, nudged to square leg.
Dan Lawrence (1-0-3-0) has been tossed the ball now.

Century for Jermaine Blackwood! His 3rd in Test cricket! There is a sigh of relief as he celebrates the landmark. A fist pump in the air, removes the helmet and soaks all the applause from the crowd. On to the ball. It was around off. Blackwood dabs it to point for a single.
On middle. Flicked to square leg where Jonny Bairstow makes a good stop.
An appeal for LBW but not given! Flatter and down the leg side. Blackwood misses his flick and gets hit on the pads. Was sliding well down.
Flatter and on middle. Blackwood flicks it well and to deep square leg. The fielder runs to his left and stops it. The batters take two runs.
Shorter and on off. Blackwood plays it late and defends it down.
Length and on middle. Blackwood clips it through mid-wicket for a couple of runs. He is three runs away from a century now.
On middle, this is hit to square leg for one.
Around off, length and Jermaine works it to covers.
Around off. Blocked out.

FOUR! A length ball, slanting around the 4th stump channel. Blackwood defends with soft hands. It goes of the outside edge and to the left of first slip for a boundary. No chance for the fielder to even stop it.
Full and on middle, flicked to deep square leg for a couple of runs. He moves into the 90s now.
Length ball, on off. Blackwood taps it back to Woakes. The keeper is standing up to the stumps.
Good news for England as Joe Root is back on the field. He has applied some ointment on the knee and is out there with some information from the coaching staff as well.
Tossed up, sliding around leg. Brathwaite prods to defend it out.
Slightly short and on off. Brathwaite cuts it past point for a brace.
Floated, on middle. Blocked out.
Full again, angling on the pads. Blackwood tucks it to square leg for a single.
Very full and on middle. Blackwood squeezes it to mid on.
Tossed up, on off. Blackwood gets back to defend.
Slower and sliding down the leg side. Brathwaite misses the flick.
Pitched up on off. Brathwaite presses forward to make the block.

Around the hips, tucked away towards short mid-wicket.
NPitched up, around off. Blackwood strokes it firmly towards covers.

Joe Root is off the pitch and he is with the team physio. Ben Stokes is the de facto skipper for the moment and Ollie Pope is the substitute fielder for Root. Maybe that slide in the previous over has done a bit of damage to his knee. Hope he is fine.
Around off, pushed out onto the off side.
At the stumps, kept out by Brathwaite.
Ripper! Slowed up, on a length and close to the off stump. The ball grips, turns and bounces a bit extra. Brathwaite looks to push at it but gets beaten past the outside edge.
Drifted into middle. Brathwaite stays solid in defense.
On off, blocked out.
Floated up, full and on leg stump. Jermaine Blackwood makes room and flicks it through mid-wicket. Joe Root gives chase and keeps it down to a single.
A length ball, around off. This is tapped straight to the fielder at cover-point.
On off, wristed away to the man at mid-wicket.
An off cutter from Woakes, full and on off. Brathwaite flicks it towards silly mid on.
Around middle and leg, dabbed down on the leg side.
On the money this time from Woakes. Brathwaite with another solid defensive block.

No more 'Stokes having a go' for now as Woakes will replace him.
This time past leg slip! Nicely drifted onto the pads, Blackwood looks to flicks it behind with soft hands but gets an inside edge past the diving fielder at leg slip for a single.

Leach goes back to 'round the wicket and drifts it into middle. Brathwaite nudges it onto the leg side.
Outside the leg stump, Brathwaite looks to leave it alone but ends up padding it away.
Flatter, around leg stump. Brathwaite blocks it off.
Leach comes from over the wicket and bowls it shorter, around leg. Brathwaite keeps it down on the leg side off the back foot.
The umpire is now having a talk with Root as well. Stokes is almost going towards Blackwood on each delivery for some verbal spat and this time both came so close, the umpires had to come in between.
A dot to finish and Ben Stokes just can't control himself. On off, blocked out. Stokes is peppering Blackwood with his words and now it's getting a bit too far.
Stokes keeps chirping back to the batter. Full and straight, dug out on the off side and this has brought the crowd alive. Stokes needs to be careful here.
A verbal agreement is going on between Stokes and Blackwood and the umpires is not having any of it

A bit of aggression shown here by the bowler and the batter. Full, around off and driven straight towards mid off. Jermaine Blackwood has a clear shout of 'No' to his partner but Stokes mimics him and Blackwood keeps shouting 'no' in response.
On off. Blocked.

Halt in play. The scissor is out as it is used on the seam of the ball.
Stokes pushes this one full and at the pads. Jermaine Blackwood pushes it out well in front of square on the leg side for a brace.

Darted on the pads. Brathwaite tucks it to square leg.
Four byes! Flatter, well outside leg and turning in. Brathwaite tries to pad it away but misses, the keeper misses to collect and it goes behind to the fence.
Flatter and on middle. Brathwaite blocks it.

Full and on off. Blackwood is squared up a bit as he tries to defend this. It goes off the splice to point.

This one spins into the right-hander, around leg. Brathwaite is rock solid in his defense.
On the pads, Brathwaite keeps it out.
Tossed up, on off. Defended.
Short ball, angling on leg. Brathwaite is not interested to play that and allows the ball to meet the pads.
Shorter and angling across, outside off. Brathwaite with deft touch, plays it to third man for a couple of runs.
Flatter and on middle. Brathwaite defends it.
On middle. Blocked out.
Length ball, around off and steep bounce there. Blackwood pushes it slightly uppishly and back to the bowler.
On a length, on off. Blackwood offers a dead bat to it.
Short and down the leg side. Blackwood sits under it.
Length and on middle. Blackwood gets behind the line to dead bat it.
A short ball, on middle. Blackwood bends his back and lets it through.
A maiden over! Flatter and on off. Brathwaite sees it out on the off side.
Slightly short and on middle. Brathwaite rocks back and defends it.
Touch fuller, angling on middle. Another solid block from Brathwaite.
Fuller and on middle. Brathwaite blocks it on the front foot.
Tossed up, on middle. Brathwaite dead bats it.

Around off, blocked back to the bowler. Jonny Bairstow is as chirpy as ever in the field. You can hear him push his side as he says 'still 270 behind guys, come on bang, bang.' He wants the bowlers to stay motivated here and that's the energy they need.
Good-length, over middle. Blackwood defends it back onto the deck.
Around the top of off, kicks off the pitch a bit. Jermaine Blackwood does well to fend it off on the off side.
Stokes goes full and straight, trying to sneak one past the bat. Blackwood stays solid in defense.

A little bit of flight, around off. Brathwaite plays it with the spin towards covers.

A deft touch from the skipper and Kraigg Brathwaite brings up a well-compiled century. Flatter, around off. Brathwaite goes deep in his crease and opens the face of the bat to guide it past backward point for a couple of runs. This has been a monumental effort in concentration from Brathwaite and he gets a round of applause from everyone in the crowd.
This is pushed through on middle. Brathwaite defends it out.
On the hips, Jermaine Blackwood hops and tucks it away towards backward square leg. The batters push hard for two and get it with ease in the end.
Angled into middle and leg, Blackwood fails to get it away leg side.
Fullish ball, around off. This is worked towards mid-wicket by Blackwood.
Now he does get the single. Full and straight, flicked away to wide mid on for a run.
Good-length, over off. Brathwaite stays solid in defsnse. He still remains on 97.
Back of a length, on the body. Brathwaite works it off the back foot towards square leg.
Around the pads, Jermaine Blackwood tickles it fine, past leg slip and comes back for the second with ease.
This one slides on with the arm. Blackwood backs away and pushes it towards cover.
Full and on middle. Blackwood with another solid block.
Fuller this time, on off. Blackwood defends it out.
Shorter this time, at the stumps. Blackwood pushes it back to the bowler off the back foot.
On middle. Blocked out.
Good-length, angled onto the pads. Blackwood turns it off his hips onto the leg side and picks up a single.

Mahmood is buzzing here! Fuller, around off and the ball just nips back in sharply and way too much. Jermaine Blackwood leaves it on line but the ball was a lot closer to the off stump than Blackwood thought.

NO BALL! Oh no! The sheer agony and Saqib Mahmood looks distraught. Mahmood bowls a signature inswinging yorker on off stump. Jermaine Blackwood is deep in his crease and just as he looks to jam it out, the ball sneaks under the willow and hits the base of off stump. Mahmood celebrates as he thinks he's got his maiden Test wicket but hold on, the third umpire signals that Mahmood has overstepped. Blackwood breathes a sigh of relief and the replay confirms that it is indeed a clear no ball.
Nicely bowled! On a driving length, in that channel around off and there is a bit of shape here for Mahmood. Jermaine Blackwood looks to drive it through covers but gets beaten past the outside edge.
On middle, pushes out by Blackwood.
Not perfectly timed. Full and straight, Brathwaite punches it back past the bowler for a run.
A length ball, on middle. Blackwood hits it on the tup, to the right of mid on and picks up a single.
Full and angling down. Brathwaite tucks it to short leg.
Tossed up, on middle, blocked out.

On the pads again. Blackwood keeps it out on the leg side.
The ball is pretty new but there seems to be a problem with it. The umpires get together to have a look and decide that the ball is fine and we are good to continue.
A full ball, on the pads. Blackwood misses his sweep and it goes off the pads to square leg.
Jack Leach has a change of ends.
Length ball, outside off. Brathwaite punches it as he gets on his toes but fails to pierce through at covers.
Again times this full ball well but finds mid on.
Full and angling on middle. Brathwaite plays with good hands but straight to mid on.
Outside off. Brathwaite pushes softly to covers.
FOUR!  Fullish and on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite on drives it well wide of mid on for a boundary.
Fuller ball, slanting on the pads. Brathwaite flicks it past square leg for a couple of runs.
Saqib Mahmood is brought back into the attack and he will bowl from the end opposite to the one he has bowled throughout this match.
Length and outside off. Blackwood punches on the up and to covers.
Another solid block from Jermaine Blackwood.
Touch fuller and on middle. Blackwood defends it out.
A slower ball, on middle. Blackwood eases it to mid-wicket.
Angles a length ball, on middle. Jermaine works it to mid-wicket.
Length and on middle, Blocked out.
Full and on middle. Brathwaite leans and tucks it to mid-wicket.
On middle. Brathwaite prods and defends this out.
Tossed up, full and on off. Blackwood looks to push but gets an outside edge to point for a single.
Leach keeps it tight, around off, pushed back.
Flatter and on off. Punched to covers.
Short and outside off, cut to deep point for a single.
A yorker this time, on middle. Blackwood digs it out nicely.
On middle, pushed to mid on.
Length ball, moving back in around off. Blackwood punches back to the bowler.
FOUR! Length and on the pads. Blackwood flicks it aerially and to square leg for a boundary.
FOUR! A length ball, width given, outside off. Blackwood square cuts it in the gap, through point. Saqib Mahmood gives a chase but to no avail.
Length ball, hint of shape there. Blackwood blocks it out.
This is floated up, a bit outside off. Brathwaite leaves it alone.
Turning away from around the pads, Brathwaite  makes a watchful block.
Darted into middle and leg. Brathwaite keeps it out.
This is is pushed through a bit quicker, at 91 kph and on middle. Brathwaite blocks it out.
Nicely drifted into middle and leg. Brathwaite strides out to defend.
Flatter and on off, tapped to cover-point.
Jack Leach (29-10-72-1) is back on.

Length, on off. Blackwood looks to turn it leg side but gets squared up a bit.
On off, Blackwood with another solid front foot defensive shot.
This is pushed well wide of the off stump. No need to play at that.
Around off, punched away to cover-point.
Pitched up, around the off stump. Blackwood defends it of the front foot.
On off, solidly defended towards covers by Brathwaite.
Much fuller, on the sixth stump line. Brathwaite leaves it alone.

Session summary: 28 overs / 82 runs / 0 wickets. Well, the hosts have certainly turned things around here in the second session. The captain and the vice-captain have stitched together a partnership of 95 runs, both going past the individual 50-run mark and have frustrated the English bowlers completely. They are still 311 runs behind but they will be feeling much better after that session and given the pitch isn't doing much and the new ball coming onto the bat nicely, the hosts might even look to keep a steady flow of runs in the final session. England need inspiration from somewhere as they have let the advantage slip and even though Jack Leach has kept up his good work, the pacers need to step up a bit more. If they do not try to be a bit more aggressive, they could be out there in the field for a lot longer and this Test match will seem to head towards another draw. Will either side press the issue in the final session? Find out soon. The post-Tea session starts at 12.30 am IST (7 pm GMT, the previous day).

West Indies seem to be in a spot of bother here and require a lot of concentration out there in the middle in order to firstly survive the follow on. Skipper Kraigg Brathwaite has been solid and hasn't looked to give away his wicket even once but runs have been hard to come by in the morning session and the pressure is mounting. Shamarh Brooks did give ample support to his skipper but got out in the 30s while playing at a loose ball. The man in form, Nkrumah Bonner though got bogged down from the start and ended up having a lapse in concentration. Brathwaite is still batting out there on 44 and he has the vice-captain, Jermaine Blackwood alongside him. Blackwood has already got lucky once and will have to be careful when he comes back out to bat. The key for the hosts will be to bat through the next session and then take it from there. Will the Windies bat for a second time today? Or will the English bowlers get frustrated by Brathwaite and co? An exciting session awaits. The post-Lunch session will start at 10.10 pm IST (4.40 pm GMT). Do join us then.

Well, it's been an engrossing first session on Day 3. West Indies scored just 43 runs and lost a couple of wickets in 27 overs. They still trail by a mammoth 393 runs. The visitors were the ones who came out with intent and Jack Leach was used right from the start. He proved to be useful as he picked up an early wicket as well. This got the visitors going but even after some good probing by the pacers, wickets were hard to come by. Finally, after some patience and perseverance, Ben Stokes did provide the breakthrough and that too a big one of Nkrumah Bonner. Stokes could have and should have had two but England didn't review an LBW decision which if they did would have seen Blackwood being sent back to the pavillion. All in all, they will be pleased with their efforts and right at the end of the session, Saqib Mahmood even got the ball to reverse.

Leach drags back his length and bowls it on off. Bonner defends it off the back foot.
FOUR! Nkrumah Bonner is the man in form and after blocking everything, he gets one away. Spilled down the leg side and this is swept away to the backward square leg fence for a boundary.
Tossed up at 92 kph and on middle. Bonner drives it to the left of the bowler.
This is slanted into middle, the ball bounces a bit extra and hits the high part of Brathwaite's willow.
On off. Blocked out.
This is a bit fuller and nipping back into middle. Brathwaite defends it off the front foot.
Uppish but safe! Full and wide, Kraigg Brathwaite reaches for this one and drives it on the bounce to the man at point.
Trying to attack the pads on the full but spills it down the leg side does Woakes. Brathwaite misses the flick.
Pitched up, on off and just shaping away a bit. Brathwaite gets a leading edge down towards cover-point.
After short spells for both Fisher and Mahmood, Chris Woakes is now brought into the attack for the first time today.
Flatter this time, this is played off the back foot towards covers. Another maiden for Jack Leach.
Quicker, drifted onto the pads and turning away. Bonner strides out to defend.
On off, kept out.
Jaffa! Drifted onto leg stump, the ball hits a crack and just turns square. Nkrumah Bonner is left bamboozled.
Sliding into middle and leg, Bonner looks to drive but gets it off the inside edge and through his pads.
Flatter, around off. Bonner opens the face of the bat and plays it towards backward point.
On off. Defended towards silly mid on.
Shorter in length, around the hips. Nkrumah Bonner drags the pull shot down to fine leg and picks up a single.
Full and straight, gently driven back towards the bowler.
This is wide of the off stump. Bonner isn't interested in playing at that one.
Pitched up, around off and there's late inward movement after the ball passes the batter. Bonner makes a watchful leave.
A length ball, close to the off pole. Bonner defends it out with soft hands towards covers.
On a length, sliding into middle and leg. Brathwaite wrists it towards square leg. Maiden over from Jack Leach.
On off this time, defended towards silly point.
Around off, Brathwaite strides out to defend.
This is speared in full and on middle. Brathwaite does well to get a bat on it.
Quicker and flatter, on off. Brathwaite defends it out.
Pushed through on off. Kept out.
This one shapes in from outside off. Bonner dead bats it onto the off side.
Shortish length, on middle. Bonner defends it back onto the deck.
Nicely bowled! Length again, angled in from outside off but the ball holds its line. Bonner looks to block from the crease but gets beaten past the outside edge.
A length ball, on the sixth stump line and there's just a bit of movement in the air for Mahmood. Bonner makes a watchful leave.
Pitched up, outside off. Nkrumah Bonner makes an easy leave.
Back of a length, on the hips. This is worked through the mid-wicket region for a single.
Saqib Mahmood comes in to replace to Matthew Fisher now.
Quicker and fuller, at the stumps. Bonner keeps it out.
Full, around middle and leg. This is eased to mid on.
Nkrumah Bonner is in at number 4.

OUT! CAUGHT! England do have the early breakthrough and it's Jack Leach who has provided it. Leach mixes up his length and bowls it a tad shorter this time and around off. The ball turns away but it is there to cut. Shamarh Brooks rocks back but is a bit too early into his cut. Brooks ends up playing a false shot and slices it towards point. Chris Woakes over there takes a good low catch and the Windies will have to start from scratch yet again.
