Commentary.Commentary: Pushed through on off and turning away. Defended off the back foot.
Flighted around leg. Kraigg Brathwaite steps out and works it towards wide mid on for a single that too against the turn.
Tossed up, on off. Brooks comes forward a bit and pushes it past the diving bowler for a single.
A length ball, slanting down leg. This is tucked away 'round the corner for a single.
A short ball, this is banged in wide of the off stump. Brooks isn't going to play at that one.
Full and wide, left alone.
On off, this is kept out on the off side.

Just short! On a good length, sliding in from outside off. There's a bit of an extra bounce on offer and Shamarh Brooks gets caught off guard. The ball goes off the gloves but falls just in front of a diving Zak Crawley at second slip.
Pitched up on off. Brooks presents a dead bat at it.
This is pushed through on middle. Brathwaite defends it off the front foot.
On middle, kept out.
Another well bowled delivery from Leach. Drifting onto middle and turning away. Shamarh Brooks does well to play at it with soft hands as he edges it down past the slip cordon for a single.
On middle, Brooks solidly keeps it out.
This is flighted on the pads. Shamarh Brooks flicks it behind square on the leg side for a couple. And again, it should have been three runs.
On off. Defended out.
On a good length, on the fifth stump line. Brathwaite keeps it out on the off side and it will be another maiden here for Matthew Fisher.
Length again, on off. Blocked out.
Around the top of off. Brathwaite pushes it out with soft hands towards mid off.
Good-length, around off. This is tapped towards covers.
This is banged in a bit and at the pads. The ball doesn't bounce much this time and Brathwaite tucks it towards Jonny Bairstow at leg gully.
Back of a length, cutting into off. Brathwaite hops back to defend.
Flatter and on off. Defended out by Brooks.
Shorter and wider, punched off the back foot through covers. Ben Stokes gives chase and slides in to cut off the boundary. The batters should have got three but they settle for a brace.
Flatter, on off. Blocked.
Just a tad bit short now, on off. Brooks goes on the back foot to block it out.
Around off, Brathwaite gets a big stride forward and strokes it towards covers for a run.
Quicker one, darted into middle at 92 kph. Brathwaite defend sit out.
This is banged in halfway down, over off. Brooks ducks under it but the ball loops over his head and dies on its way to the keeper.
Sliding onto the pads, tucked away to deep square leg for one.
Full again, on off and slanting in. Brathwaite manages to keep it out.
Fullish ball, around middle and just swinging in a bit. Brathwaite bunts it out on the leg side.
Length again, around off. This is pushed away on the up towards covers.
A length ball, on off and just nipping back in a touch. Brathwaite defends it from his crease.
Floated up on off. Brooks defends it out.
Around middle, Brathwaite looks to push it out but gets it just to the right of short leg and scampers through for a single.
Peach! Lovely drift and then sharp turn again from Jack Leach. Brathwaite presses forward to block but gets beaten past the outside edge.
This is sliding into middle and leg. Brooks flicks it through mid-wicket and picks up the first run of the day.
On middle. Kept out.
What a delivery to start off with! Slowed up, at 77 kph and drifted into off. The ball grips and turns away sharply leaving Brooks completely bamboozled.
Jack Leach (9-4-21-0) to partner Matthew Fisher from the opposite end.
Fisher starts Day 3 with a maiden! On a good length, angled into middle. There's a bit of an extra bounce again as Brathwaite dabs it down on the leg side.
Pitched up on off. This one stays a tad low but Brathwaite stays solid in defense.
Around the top of off, kept out.
On a good length, over middle. Brathwaite looks to defend but gets taken aback by the extra bounce but manages to keep it down.
A touch fuller this time, around off. Brathwaite presses forward to defend.
Fisher is on the money right from the off. A length ball, on off. Brathwaite blocks it out.

We are set for the start of Day 3! The players and the umpires are out in the middle. The overnight batters for the Windies, Kraigg Brathwaite and Shamarh Brooks take guard. Matthew Fisher to start proceedings with the ball here. Let's go...

PITCH REPORT - Samuel Badree is pitchside and is assessing the playing conditions. Badree mentions that the weather cleared out pretty soon and there's going to be an uninterrupted day of action. Mentions that there are some cracks developing as we go on. Leach mentioned that he would want to bowl wicket to wicket and that's the way it should be on this pitch and if there's a bit of turn, the hosts will have a big challenge in front of them.

Jack Leach is up for a quick chat. Jack says that there's a little bit of turn there and it's a slow wicket. Adds that he enjoys bowling from the top end and go against the breeze and will look to carry on today as well. Also adds that it's just about hitting the right areas and staying patient. Mentions that he wants to keep the wickets in play and beat both the edges.

Shamarh Brooks is down for a chat. Brooks says he had to wait his turn but is happy to be back home and get the chance, will look to make the most of it. He adds that it was quite challenging as they were out in the field for almost 2 days but him and Kraig just looked to stay positive and score runs as well. Mentions that Leach got some turn and everyone knows how dangerous Stokes can be.

There has been a bit of rain around in the morning but the forecast looks good for the rest of the day. The massive news though came from the English camp. In a statement, it was revealed that Mark Wood will fly back home and see a specialist and for now he will be on an indefinite break from cricket which means he will miss the entirety of the upcoming Indian T20 League. We wish him the speediest of recoveries.

The pitch is not giving much assistance to the pacers but spinners started to get some turn in the last session of Day 2 and it is expected to get more friendly for the spinners as well. Jack Leach bowled tight lines and asked some questions but Brathwaite in particular negotiated well. Still 436 runs behind, West Indies will hope to start the day on a positive note while England will look to create some early inroads and take control of the match. The first session coming up in a bit.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 3 of the coverage between West Indies and England. The hosts are off to a great start after being asked to tackle the last one hour on Day 2. Despite losing John Campbell early on, skipper Kraigg Brathwaite and Shamarh Brooks showed good composure and also scored runs at a decent rate. They’ll hope to start the day in the same fashion.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

Earlier it was carnage from Root and Stokes as they both scored centuries. Stokes in particular played an entertaining innings and scored in quick time as well. Then, Woakes and Foakes combined and helped England post a total excess of 500. In reply, West Indies lost a wicket early but Brathwaite and Brooks look solid after that. The moving day will be very crucial as England will look for early wickets while the host will hope these two to start in the same fashion as they ended. Day 3 will start at 7.30 pm IST (2 pm GMT). But the build up will begin much early. So, do join us for the same. Till then, Adios.

Ben Stokes is up for a quick chat. He says that it was good to be out there and he capitalized on the good work laid out by Dan Lawrence and Root and once he got in he just tried to score as many runs as possible. Adds that it is important to identify the right situation and when the platform was laid, he tried to get the game moving quickly so that they could have a pop at the end with the ball. Mentions that surprisingly the pitch has changed late and hopes they can get wickets early non Day 3. About his century, he adds that with everything that's going on in his personal life in the past couple of years, it was a memorable century.

It was a dream debut for Matthew Fisher as he got the solitary wicket of the Windies innings. The other bowlers were tight in their lengths and lines as well. Leach bowled some superb deliveries but he was well mediated by the hosts. It started spinning more later in the day and looks like Leach will be very important to get a breakthrough on the moving day.

A decent last session and both the teams will be happy at the end of Day 2. West Indies were off to a brilliant start but they soon lost Campbell. Since then, Kraigg Brathwaite and Shamarh Brooks negotiated the English bowlers and scored at a brisk rate as well. They have built a good foundation and will hope to continue the same on Day 3.
Well negated by Shamarh Brooks and he has seen it through. This is flatter and on off. Brooks defends it off the back foot towards short cover and that will be curtains on Day 2!
Turning sharply from a nagging length. Brooks goes deep in his crease and plays at it with soft hands towards the gully region.
A quick chat between Leach, Root and Stokes. A slip, gully, silly point and short leg in place.
This is pushed through on off and Shamarh Brooks defends it right off the middle of the bat past silly point.
On off, dabbed down towards silly point.
A touch quicker, on middle and turning away. Brooks keeps it out this time.
Jaffa! Nicely drifted into middle, on a length and the ball just takes off after pitching. The ball is bowled at 80 kph, it turns away sharply and bounces extra. Shamarh Brooks is left bamboozled.
Dragged down now, on leg stump. Brooks pulls it down to fine leg for a single.
This is fired in full and outside off. Brooks doesn't play at it.
Nicely bowled! Flighted, on off and Lawrence puts a bit of revs on that one. Brathwaite nudges it towards square leg for one.
Around middle, gently pushed towards mid on.
On a length, around off. The ball turns in and Lawrence gets a bit of bounce as well. Brathwaite dabs it down on the leg side.
Around off, pushed towards the cover region for an easy single.
Dan Lawrence to roll his arm now.
FOUR! A bit of width on offer and Kraigg Brathwaite is waiting for it. Brathwaite rocks back and strokes it through backward point for a welcome boundary.
And again! Leach is just bowling it at the same pace and around off. Brathwaite with another easy block.
Around off, kept down past the slip cordon.
This is pushed through on off. The ball turns away a bit and Brathwaite plays it well.
Slightly tossed up, full and staright. Brathwaite drives it towards mid on.
Angled into middle and leg, a touch quicker though. Brathwaite keeps it out.
Fuller in length, gently driven towards mid off. Maiden!
Good-length, around the top of off. Brooks goes back and across to push it out on the off side.
This pitched up, a bit wide of off stump. Brooks isn't going to play at that one.
On off. Blocked off.
Top delivery and a very good leave in the end by Shamarh Brooks. Length, very close to the off pole and holding its line. Brooks looks to have a poke at it but decides against it.
Full, on the sixth stump line at 138 clicks. Brooks shoulders arms to that one.
Around off. Blocked.
Good comeback delivery fro Leach. Slower through the air, turning away quite a bit from middle. Brathwaite edges it down with soft hands towards the slip cordon.
FOUR! Drift on offer but Jack Leach errs in line this time as he bowls it quicker. Kraigg Brathwaite rocks back and cuts it into the point fence. The 50 partnership is up between theses two.
Nicely bowled! Drifted into middle and leg, at a nagging length and turning away nicely. Kraigg Brathwaite with another good forward defensive shot.
Nicely drifted into middle. Brathwaite strides forward to make the block.
Floated, full and on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite clips it past mid-wicket and picks up a couple of runs.
Length ball, outside off. Brooks leaves it alone.
Full ball, inswinger, on middle. Brooks on drives it to mid on.
Length ball, outside off. Brathwaite tries to nudge it down but gets an inside edge onto the pads. The ball rolls to covers and they take a quick single.
This time hits it through covers for a single.
Short of a length, outside off. Brooks punches it hard and to point where Lees certainly saves a boundary,

Darted on the pads. Brathwaite nudges it to square leg.

Kraigg Brathwaite right away reviews the decision made for LBW. He reckons he has knicked that and that is the only thing that can save him. The replays roll in and it does seem that there's bat involved and UltraEdge confirms the existence of a bottom edge onto the pads. NOT OUT!

An appeal and up goes the finger. Brathwaite though reviews it straightaway and he looked confident as well. The replay shows there was a big spike as the ball passes the bat. Good review.
Spin there again, around off. Brathwaite defends on the front foot.
Floated, full, outside off. Brathwaite prods and shoulders arms to it.
Tossed up, full and on off. Brathwaite prods and defends.

Extra bounce this time, outside off. Brooks easily leaves it.

Length again, on middle. Brooks wrists it but straight to mid-wicket.
Length ball, angling around off. Brooks defends with a straight bat.
Length ball, outside off. Brooks hops and blocks it out. A late no ball called for overstepping.
Length and outside off. Brooks shoulders arms to it.
Short ball, on off. Brooks is not tempted to pull this one.
On a good length, on off. Kraigg Brathwaite pushes it towards the cover region.
Slanted into middle and leg, kept out on the leg side. The English crowd is getting louder and louder every second, pushing their team to pick up a wicket.
Pitched up, around off. Brathwaite shoulders arms to it.
Fullish delivery around off. Shamarh Brooks doesn't quite time the cover drive but still picks up a single.
Full, close to the off pole and left alone by Brooks.
Back of a length, around off. This is caressed towards cover-point.

On a good length over off. Saqib Mahmood is keeping it around the 135 kph mark. Kraigg Brathwaite with another defensive block off the back foot.
Back of a length, around off. Brathwaite dabs it down towards cover-point.

Around the top of off, at 137 clicks. Brathwaite keeps it out on the off side.
Mahmood starts off with a full ball, on the fifth stump line. Brathwaite watches it zip through to the keeper.
Saqib Mahmood to bowl now.
Full and wide, left alone by Shamarh Brooks.

NO BALL! Pitched up, on off. Brooks defends it off the front foot. Stokes has overstepped and a no ball is called.
Nicely bowled shorter ball. This is angled into off but goes straight through. Shamarh Brooks does well to sway away from the line of the ball.
Length this time, around off and at 139 kph. Brooks defends it back onto the deck.
Back of a length, around off. Brooks hops back and keeps it down towards cover.
Stokes bangs it in short and over middle. Brooks ducks under it.
On off. Brathwaite defends it under the eyeline.
Shorter again, pushed towards covers by Brooks for a quick single.
FOUR! Just straying a bit there Jack Leach and Shamarh Brooks takes full advantage. Down the leg side, paddled away into the fine leg fence for a boundary.
Flatter again, darted into middle. There's an extra bit of bounce as Brooks looks to defend but manages to keep it down on the off side.
Quicker and flatter, on off. Brooks works it off the back foot towards short cover.
This is pushed through fuller and around off. Brooks blocks it out.
Pitches it up, on middle. Brathwaite leans and defends it off the outer portion.
Full, outside off, left alone.
Length and outside off. Brathwaite defends away from the body, onto the off side.
Length and angling on off. Brathwaite covers his stumps and blocks it.
Length and on middle, flicked to deep square leg for a single.

Drinks! As we head into the final hour's play on Day 2, the players take a drinks break. It has been a good contest between bat and bat at the start of the Windies innings and the debutant Matthew Fisher has been the most effective bowler, picking up a wicket of his second delivery in Test cricket. Jack Leach too has looked dangerous and has got the ball to turn but a flurry of boundaries from Kraigg Brathwaite and Shamarh Brooks has seen them muster up a few runs as well. Really interesting to see now as to who heads into Day 3 with the advantage. Also, Ben Stokes is introduced into the attack.
On middle. Defended out.
Quicker again, on middle. Brathwaite prods and defends it solidly.
Shorter, outside off, spinning away. Left alone.
Quicker one, on off. Brathwaite again blocks it.
Tossed up, full and on off. Brathwaite dead bats it.
Very full and on off, pushed to covers.
FOUR! Fuller and outside off. Brooks gets low and caresses it through covers for a boundary.

NOT OUT! A foot forward and that might have been a good catch. Fisher goes wide of the crease and angles a full ball, around off. Brooks closes his bat face slightly as he tries to defend on the leg side but gets an outside edge to second slip where Crawley gets his hands low to take it but he seems to have not taken it cleanly. The catch is taken upstairs and the replay shows the ball was grounded.

Is that a clean catch? Everyone on the ground seems it is but the man who took, Zak Crawley doesn't seem as excited as everyone else. The decision is sent upstairs and the soft signal is NOT OUT. The third umpire checks it from a few different angles and concludes that as Crawley took the catch, the ball got grounded a bit. No conclusive evidence to overturn the on-field call and Brooks survives.
Short and well outside off. Brooks watches it sail over and to the keeper.
Down the leg side. Brooks misses his flick.
Length and outside off. Brooks plays it late and without much commitment, to the keeper.
Length and on off. Brooks keeps it out.
Leach comes over the wicket this time, flatter and on off. Brathwaite blocks it off the back foot.
Tossed up, on off. Brathwaite with another solid block.
Full and on off. Brathwaite defends on the front foot.
On middle. Blocked out.
Two byes! Flatter and down the leg side. Brathwaite misses his flick. The keeper fails to collect and the batters take two byes.
Tossed up, on middle. Brathwaite strides forward to defend it.

Fuller and outside off. Brooks times his drive but Stokes does well at covers to stop it.

Length ball, hint of outswing, on off. Brooks gets a straight bat down to defend.
Full and on middle. Brooks leans and solidly blocks it.
This is pushed through on off. Brathwaite goes on the back foot to keep it out.
Around middle and leg, played with soft hands towards short leg by Brathwaite.
Full and around the leg stump, Brathwaite nudges it behind towards short fine leg.
Around off, defended towards short cover this time.
Quicker and shorter, around off. Brathwaite goes deep in his crease to keep it out towards covers.
Flatter, on off and at 90 kph. Brathwaite presses forward to make the block.
Around the top of off, kept out on the off side.
Edged and four! On a driving length, outside off. Shamarh Brooks pushes away from the body and edges it down to the vacant third man fence for a boundary.
Good-length on off, Brathwaite plays it off the back foot onto the off side and collects a single.
This is dragged down around off. Brooks hangs back and dabs it through covers for a single.
Brilliant delivery and a leave to match. Fullish delivery, angled into off and getting it to deviate away off the pitch. Brooks makes a watchful leave.
Angled onto the pads, tucked away behind square on the leg side for a single by Brathwaite.
Around off and turning away, left alone.
Tossed up again, wide of off. Kept out on the off side.
Peach! Tossed up, full and around off. The ball grips and turns away sharply. Brooks does well not to edge that one.
Half an appeal, nothing more. On a length, around middle. Brooks gets a big stride forward and looks to sweep but misses. He misses and gets hit on the pads but the umpire remains unmoved.
FOUR! Short and wide, Shamarh Brooks rocks back and slaps it through cover-point for a boundary.
Leach starts off with a flatter one, pushed through around off. Brooks can't get it past point.
Jack Leach is into the attack.
Maiden! Full and straight, Brathwaite times the straight drive well but the fielder at mid on does well to make a sharp stop down to his left.

Full and close to the off pole. Brathwaite defends it out solidly.
Down the leg side, tucked away off the hips to fine leg for one more.

Length ball, on the pads, tucked to square leg.
Outside off, left alone.
Length ball, shaping away, outside off and steep bounce as well. All for Brooks to shoulders his arms.
Brooks with yet another easy leave.
Outside off, on a length. Brooks shoulders arms to it.
A length ball, outswinger this time and Brooks covers his stumps nicely.
Length again. Brathwaite dead bats it on the off side.
Length ball, on off. Kept out.
Full and on middle. Brooks flicks it through mid-wicket. Saqib Mahmood gives a chase and saves a run.
Four byes! A pacy short ball, on middle, the ball hows late movement and goes to the left of the keeper. Hard for him to catch it and the ball finds the fence.

Extra pace, bounce, outside off. Brooks offers no shot.
Shamarh Brooks is in early at number 3.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! A dream start for the debutant and he is running all over with joy in his eyes! A length ball, in good channel, around 4th stump channel. The debutant, Matthew Fisher to share the new ball with Chris Woakes. Let's see what he's made of.
Fuller and outside off. Left alone.
Length and on the pads, flicked wide of deep square leg for a couple of runs.
FOUR! Good start for the Windies! Fuller and on off. Brathwaite this time, leans and punches down to long off for another boundary.
Length ball, outside off. Brathwaite shoulders arms to it.
FOUR! West Indies and Brathwaite are off the mark! A length ball, outside off, width there as well. Brathwaite punches off the back foot through point for a boundary.
A length ball, on off, hint of away shape. Brathwaite defends it to mid-wicket.
We are back for the middle session! The players stride out to the middle. Kraigg Brathwaite and John Campbell are the openers for West Indies. Chris Woakes to start with the ball. Let's go...
... DAY 5, SESSION 2 ...

ENGLAND HAVE DECLARED! As expected! They have given themselves two sessions weather permitting to take the 10 wickets, whereas Windies will have to chase down 282 to win. Will they go for it? Don’t see that happening.

If we resume on time after break, England would have probably declared and it will/should be Windies batting. A good second session awaits. The post-Lunch session should start at 10.53 pm IST (5.23 pm GMT) unless the raingods have some other plans.

And we assume we won’t be seeing England bat again in this game after the break! They lead by 281 and that should probably be enough. They came out all guns blazing and all the batters went after the bowlers right from the word go. A few played some handy cameos to take the lead up to 19 short of 300.

PITCH REPORT - Sir Curtly Ambrose reckons that it's a very dry surface. There will be variable bounce from time to time and he expects the pitch to play the same way.

Jonny Bairstow is up for a chat. He says that the attitiude that the guys showed was great. Mentions that they need to dig deep again if they have to force a result today. Tells that the further they go, there's more pressure to accelerate or for them to bat out for a draw. Informs that some balls have kept low, the way Jack Leach bowled, he was unlucky. Tells that when they come to bowl today, it'll be interesting. Informs that they will bat normally in the first half an hour.

Veerasammy Permaul is up for a chat. He says that it's not a wicket where you can go and blast as a batsman, you need to be patient. Mentions that the faster you bowl, it becomes easier. Tells that one got to bowl slower. States that in T20 cricket, he has opened with the white ball so it's not a new role for him to open with the red cherry as well.

Windies on the other hand, need wickets and in a heap. That is the only slender hope they have of a win. We have seen this England batting fall apart before and the hosts will hope it is one of those days. The first session will probably give us an idea as to which way is this game heading to.

Kraigg Brathwaite, Windies skipper and Man of the Match, says he wants to thank to the Windies fan for the support. He just wanted to play straight and stick to the basics. Mentions they would love the wickets to provide assistance to the pacers but it was a big effort from them and he is pleased. Adds to okay the knock he did in his hometown was really good and he is very happy. Ends by saying it was a tremendous team effort, Blackwood played really well and he is proud of the fight they showed.

Joe Root, England skipper, says Mahmood and Leach were brilliant, there has not been a lot from the wicket but they have shown a lot of skills and it is great to see the delight on the faces of them when they were picking wickets. States they did not want to make it too close and give a lot of overs, you can look in hindsight and feel they could have declared earlier but credit to the Windies for the way they played. Adds they’ll have to see the kind of wicket they get and then decide what team to play. Further says it is good to see the way Leach is bowling and he is finding his feet at this level.

Then with a lead of around 100, England added quick runs and set a target of over 280. They have themselves around 60 overs to have a go at the Windies but that was never going to be enough on this placid surface to bowl a team out.

In reply, the Windies batted close to six sessions but still fell around 100 short of England's total. However, the important thing was they took a lot of time out of the game which is what they were aiming for. Kraigg Brathwaite and Blackwood were brilliant with tons. The former especially who batted close to 500 balls.
The game though goes down as yet another one dominated by the batters. It was England first who scored above 500 courtesy tons from Stokes and Root.

England on the other hand, did their all though on Day 5! Played with aggression earlier on, scored quickly. Declared with two sessions to go. Got wickets at regular intervals but it just wasn't enough. The wicket just did not play its part. It did not detoriate a lot and was still good for batting. Saqib was really good and so was Leach but in the end, Joshua and Brathwaite showed great resilience to ensure their side did not lose the game.

The two captains have seen shaking hands which means that is the end of the game and it ends in another draw. Credit to both Joshua and Brathwaite. The two joined association with around 15 overs to go, it was a tricky period but the two have fought hard and come out with flying colors. A word of appreciation for Brathwaite who is the difference between Windies heading into the third Test all level and not 1 down. A monumental effort from the skipper and he has led from the front.

Windies will hope the two can keep going and continue to battle it out. England on the other hand, will feel if they get one of these two early, that could well break one end open. Join us for the final session of this Test and something tells me it is going to be an exciting one. The final session will start at 1.15 am IST (7.45 pm GMT, previous day).

It is yet again that pair, Brathwaite and Blackwood, the skipper and the vice captain leading the fight back for their side. Had it not been for the two, Windies would have been in huge trouble. They though have once again made draw the most likely result after England had turned the tide in their favor with three early wickets.

OUT! CAUGHT! Jack Leach strikes in his first over and he is once again showing his worth. Great review taken by England. Fantastic start by Jack Leach.  Pitches this around off and it turns into Campbell sharply again. He looks to defend off the front foot but gets the inside edge onto his pads and the ball loops in the air towards short leg. Lees there takes a fine catch and England appeal. However, the umpire is not interested and England review. The replays roll in and the UltraEdgte shows that there is glove involved there and England have an early breakthrough here.
Commentary.Howout: c Alex Lees b Jack Leach
